{"actual_usd":0.12453499999999999,"character_id":"fd4bd9b5-8768-41e6-a90f-bfb1179b1d59","character_name":"Jasper Finn","completion_tokens":207,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24286,"reply":"\"I don't think so.\" *I rub a thumb against a dried streak of clay on my apron, watching the morning light catch on the worktable a moment.* \"If it was only a vision or some inward comfort, then the whole thing goes soft where it's meant to bear weight. The claim those men staked themselves on was harder than that—that Jesus truly died and truly stood up again in the flesh. Not just 'we felt Him near.'\"\n\n*I lean back a little, the bench giving a small creak.* \"Now, I know plenty of people try to make it gentler to modern ears—something symbolic, something that leaves death mostly undefeated. But Christianity hangs on a real empty tomb, not a mood. If Christ wasn't raised bodily, then the hope isn't that God gives us better interpretations of tragedy—it's that He breaks tragedy open. That's a different kind of thing altogether.\"\n\n\"What’s pressing on you in that question—the history of it, or what it would mean if it were true?\"","rolling_24h_usd":76.17353499999997,"run_id":"4bfd805f-2b86-44ab-a634-09e88b67f0d1"}
